  #courtney
  section.main
    .row
      .medium-4.columns
        img(src='/assets/images/event/speakers/courtney.jpg')

      .medium-8.columns
        h2 Courtney White
        p A former archaeologist and Sierra Club activist, Courtney White dropped out of the ‘conflict industry’ in 1997 to co-found the Quivira Coalition, a nonprofit dedicated to building bridges between ranchers, conservationists, public land managers, scientists and others around practices that improve land health (see <a href="http://www.quiviracoalition.org">www.quiviracoalition.org</a>). Today, his writing and conservation work focuses on building economic and ecological resilience on working landscapes, with a special emphasis on carbon ranching and the new agrarian movement.
        p His writing has appeared in numerous publications, including Farming, Acres Magazine, Rangelands, the Natural Resources Journal and Solutions. His essay The Working Wilderness: a Call for a Land Health Movement” was published by Wendell Berry in 2005 in his collection of essays titled The Way of Ignorance.
        p In 2008, Island Press published Courtney’s book Revolution on the Range: the Rise of a New Ranch in the American West. He co-edited, with Dr. Rick Knight, Conservation for a New Generation, also published by Island Press in 2008.
        p In 2010, Courtney was given the Michael Currier Award for Environmental Service by the New Mexico Community Foundation. In 2012, he was a writer-in-residence at the U Cross Foundation, in northwestern Wyoming, and he was the first Aldo Leopold Writer-in-Residence at Mi Casita, in Tres Piedras, New Mexico, courtesy of the Aldo Leopold Foundation and the U.S. Forest Service.
        p In 2012, he published a collection of black-and-white photographs of the American West in an online book titled The Indelible West. It includes a Foreword by Wallace Stegner (written in 1992). See: <a href="http://www.indeliblewest.com">www.indeliblewest.com</a>
        p In 2014, his book Grass, Soil, Hope: a Journey through Carbon Country was published by Chelsea Green Press and included a Foreword by Michael Pollan.
        p In early 2015, Counterpoint Press published a collection of his essays titled Age of Consequences: a Chronicle of Concern and Hope with an Introduction by Wendell Berry.
        p In fall 2015, Chelsea Green Press will publish his book Two Percent Solutions for the Planet: 50 Low-cost, Low-tech, Nature-based Practices for Combating Hunger, Drought and Climate Change.
        p More of Courtney’s work can be found on his web site: <a href="http://www.awestthatworks.com">www.awestthatworks.com</a>
        p He lives in Santa Fe, New Mexico, with his family and a backyard full of chickens.

  #cindy
  section.main
    .row
      .medium-4.columns
        img(src='/assets/images/event/speakers/cindy.jpg')

      .medium-8.columns
        h2 Dr. Cindy Daley
        p Dr. Cindy Daley’s mission is to bring ecological farming practices into the academic setting by creating a living laboratory for students to become directly involved in organic dairy production practices. In 2007, she was involved in creating the only academically-based Organic Dairy Program (ODP) in the Western Region, a true pasture based system where students are directly involved in the process including learning the fundamentals of Holistic Planned Grazing, organic pasture management and silage production, preventative nutrition for herd health, milking hygiene, milk quality, organic calf management, and whole farm systems planning. Positions on the Student Dairy Management Team are very competitive.

        p Dr. Daley is also actively involved in grassfed beef trials and research. She is famous for her recent paper on fatty acid profile and antioxidant content in grassfed beef and it’s comparison to grainfed beef.

        p Dr. Daley is actively involved in a national consortium of researchers working to bring a variety of educational materials and research bulletins on-line to benefit organic producers as well as the extension service, organic certification personnel and agricultural educators. The applied research program is driven by the recommendations of organic dairy producers throughout the Western Region. Active research projects include reduced grain feeding and the use of soil amendments to improve forage quality and net profitability; the effect of pasture DMI on milk nutrient content and the use of fodder as a grain alternative in mid-size dairy operations.

        p She is also starting her own dairy in Oroville, CA called Sweet Grass Organics <a href="http://www.sweetgrassorganics.com/">sweetgrassorganics.com</a>.


